A y/n code representing eligibility for Euro system monetary policy operations. See the ecb_cds table in the GCODES Database Viewer for a complete list of codes. Up to January 1, 2007, eligible assets belonged to one of two categories: tier one consisted of marketable debt instruments fulfilling uniform euro area-wide eligibility criteria specified by the European Central Bank (ECB); tier two consisted of additional assets, marketable and non-marketable, which are of particular importance to national financial markets and banking systems and for which eligibility criteria was established by the national central banks, subject to the minimum eligibility criteria established by the ECB. This field is used to indicate the regulatory qualifier required by EU Regulation to denote the ratings of structured finance instruments. It is also used to save other specific suffixes assigned by different rating agencies. For example, '(emr)' or '(mmf)' for Fitch ratings. The '(sf)' symbol indicates that the security is a structured finance instrument. It is requested by EU to append the suffix to the rating codes. Note: A space needs to be included when appending the qualifier to the rating. For example, AAA (sf), mxAAA (sf), AAA (sf)/NEG. In addition to the '(sf)' indicator, Fitch has also implemented two new ratings suffixes: '(mmf)' and '(emr)' to increase the transparency to what the rating addresses. For example, '(emr)' denotes embedded risk. This is present in directly issued structured notes where the embedded risk is the credit risk of a third party or of a basket of third parties. The suffix '(mmf)' indicates that this rating is applicable for a Money Market Fund.
